extended_text.content:
In one of the first multiple sculptures produced at Gemini, Lichtenstein looked back at arte moderne of the 1930s, specifically the "Heads" painted by Russian constructivist Alexei Jawlensky, in which the language of Cubism was resuited to the machine age.

Lichtenstein said: "What interested me was -‘what in the world a modern head could be about'-I mean to make a man look as if its been made by an engineering draftsman." Accordingly, he recreated an arte moderne painting as an engineered and machined work in solid brass.

15212.description: Edition of 53 (in a series of monotypes)
15212.credit_line: Gift of the Contemporary Art Society
15212.medium_support: woodblock monotype on handmade paper with hand-coloring and collage element in steel frame
15212.inscription: inscribed in white: J---- B---- inscribed in red paint: 3274704

extended_text.content:
Beginning as a pastime to focus his thinking in 1968, Borofsky began counting to infinity. He soon began signing his work with the number he had just reached. When he made Man with a Briefcase at Gemini in 1990, the number was 3,274,676. While each of the 58 prints in the edition had the same central woodcut figure, they were otherwise unique and, therefore, numbered sequentially; this impression is 3,274,704.

"At that time, I was carrying a briefcase to my exhibitions . . . It was my own personal self-portrait, but it also translated to an archetypal image of the worker with briefcase."
-Jonathan Borofsky, 2002

13692.title: Ground Zero 8: Target Babylon III
13692.credit_line: Mary V. Black Art Endowment Fund
13692.medium_support: machine stitched, embroidered, interlaced 16 mm microfilm, 70 mm leader film, black and white copies on rag paper, acetate transperencies, color magazine pictures, netting, colored threads, paint, AC-64 polymer medium, fabric backed

extended_text.content:
Artist’s Statement

This piece is inspired by Revelations, in the New Testament, and the writing of the 19th-century seer Nostradamus. The biblical Babylon is the modern-day New York City. Hidden in the dark wings are terrorist figures who represent the current “anti-Christ.” Other graphic symbols representing nuclear bombs, ICBM’s and radiation are also present. Fluorescent colors contrasted with large areas of black and depict the dynamic transitions that occur during and after a bomb blast. This piece represents a design where radial balance and intense colors form the target area in an aerial perspective view of nuclear ground zero.

-Arturo Alonzo Sandoval

"Di Suvero's sculptures are widely known for a rough geometry of forms in balanced motion. The materials are usually mixed and fundamentally inelegant-wooden or steel beams, chain, stone. Di Suvero's prints, if not outright sketches for sculptures, capture something of the spirit of these works."
-Gene Baro, The Brooklyn Museum, 1976

Di Suvero had made an edition of small sculptures with Ken Tyler at Gemini G.E.L., but his first lithographs were made at Tyler Graphics Ltd. in New York in 1976.

extended_text.content:
Throughout his career, Close has rematerialized photographic portraits of friends in a wide array of expressive paintings and prints.

Always testing the technical limits of printmaking, Jack Lemon worked with Close at Landfall Press to progressively reduce four images of Keith and retain the legibility of each while printing from eleven lithographic stones on an 88-inch sheet of paper.

"If I was going to do a print, I wanted to do something where I didn't know how to do it. And the printer didn't know how to do it either."
-Chuck Close

63907.title: Abu Ghraib
63907.credit_line: Gift of Ann M. and Chris Stack
63907.provenance: Purchased by Ann and Chris Stack, Indianapolis, from the publisher, Gemini G.E.L., Los Angeles, California, 2004.
63907.inscription:
Inscribed in pencil, below image, l.l.: 1/250
Inscribed in pencil, below image, l.c.: ABU GHRAIB
signed and dated in pencil, below image, l.r.: R Serra/2004
blindstamp, l.r.: [ Gemini]
stamped, verso, l.l: Published by Gemini G.E.L. LLC / Los Angeles, California / c 2004 Richard Serra and Gemini G.E.L. LLC
rights: © Richard Serra/Artists Rights Society (ARS), New York

extended_text.content:
Since its release to the media in April of 2004, the picture of a hooded prisoner suffering torture at the hands of United States soldiers at Abu Ghraib prison in Iraq has circulated widely. The image is shown here in a lithograph by Richard Serra, who rendered the silhouette in rough strokes of an oil stick.

Known primarily for his massive steel sculptures, Serra first drew this figure as a political statement, with block letters reading "Stop Bush." He reproduced the work in art magazines; on a billboard; and as a flyer circulated freely online, at conventions, and at the 2006 Whitney Biennial alongside the original drawing. The figure here, with no written statement, is a testament to the power of an image and its life through popular distribution.
extended_text.title: Gallery Label

9365.title: The Stoneness of the Stone
9365.credit_line: Gift of Dr. and Mrs. T. R. Hensel
9365.medium_support: ink on Twinrocker hand-made paper, lithograph
9365.inscription: signed and inscribed in pencil, L.R.: Motherwell 67/75
rights: © Licensed by VAGA, New York, NY

extended_text.content:
Unlike the other major Abstract Expressionist painters, Robert Motherwell was an avid printmaker. His satisfaction varied depending on the skill of his collaborating printer (in this case Ken Tyler) and the subtle qualities of the chosen paper (here Twinrocker handmade paper from Brookston, Indiana).

Tyler's mentor, Garo Antreasian, found in this image, "the grace, command and noble austerity of a Zen brushmaster" . . . Tyler's "sheer mastery of processing and printing the magnificent washes is unsurpassed; it rises to complement perfectly the touch of Motherwell's hand."
extended_text.title: Gallery Label

61320.title: hat (masks)
61320.description: Gold leather hat with 3-dimensionsal faces on it.
61320.credit_line: Purchased with funds provided by Benjamin B. Green-Field Foundation

extended_text.content:
Benjamin Green-Field, "Chicago's Mad Hatter," and his sister Bessie opened a millinery store in Chicago in 1920. They combined their first names to create the famous Bes-Ben logo. Within eight years the duo had expanded their business to include five shops, and their hats had become a necessary adornment for Chicago's socialites.

Bes-Ben's hats were generally sensible and traditional until 1941, when Green-Field's creativity and sense of humor began to surface in his designs. Among the unusual items that began to appear in his hats were firecrackers, skyscrapers, animals, bugs, fruit, doll furniture, palm trees, cigarette packages, and even Folies-Bergère dancers.

The prices for Green-Field's creations, which originally ranged from $37.75 to $1,000, tended to exclude women on a tight budget. Every summer, however, he would clean out his inventory for the new season at a midnight sale, marking down the hats to as little as $5. Then, at two in the morning, he would toss the rest out of the front door to waiting bargain hunters.
extended_text.title: Gallery Label

61790.title: Untitled #7
61790.credit_line: Henry F. and Katherine D. DeBoest Memorial Fund
61790.medium_support: acrylic and graphite collage on panel

extended_text.content:
A child is snatched from his bicycle, the strong arm of his abductor muffling his cries. In an adjacent pane, concerned parents, rendered in sketched gray tones, call out for their missing child.

Kojo Griffin, who studied child psychology at Morehouse College, uses animal figures to present vignettes of human interactions. Griffin uses this device to represent social situations ranging from the mundane (a tired parent with a crying infant) to the truly traumatic (a firing squad, a child abduction as seen here) without referring to particular types or clichés. The arena for these activities is a landscape of abstract graphic design.
extended_text.title: Gallery Label

17182.title: day dress
17182.medium_support: slubbed raw silk, trimmed with silk shantung
17182.provenance: Betty Furness (19161994), New York; through (Stan Weaver, New York); given to the Indianapolis Museum of Art (1985).

extended_text.content:
This dress from the last Traina-Norell collection of 1960 displays a strong Chanel influence. In the spring of 1955, Coco Chanel introduced suits with flapped pockets outlined with piping in a contrasting color. In this dress Norell used black silk shantung piping to outline the front panel, the flaps of the two patched pockets, the collar, and the cuffs to create a dramatic contrast.

The dress was worn by Betty Furness during her on-camera appearances at the 1960 presidential conventions— and in 1967 by Furness’s daughter, when she held the Bible during her mother’s swearing-in ceremony as the first consumer adviser to President Johnson.
extended_text.title: Gallery Label
